#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:23
msgid "## The boot process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:25
msgid ""
"It is important to understand the boot process of Linux in order to be able "
"to solve problems that may occur."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:27
msgid "The boot process includes:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:29
msgid "### The BIOS startup"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:31
msgid ""
"The **BIOS** (Basic Input/Output System) performs the **POST** (power on "
"self test) to detect, test and initialize the system hardware components."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:33
msgid "It then loads the **MBR** (Master Boot Record)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:35
msgid "### The Master boot record (MBR)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:37
msgid ""
"The Master Boot Record is the first 512 bytes of the boot disk. The MBR "
"discovers the boot device and loads the bootloader **GRUB2** into memory and "
"transfers control to it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:39
msgid "The next 64 bytes contain the partition table of the disk."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:41
msgid "### The GRUB2 bootloader"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:43
msgid ""
"The default bootloader for the Rocky 8 distribution is **GRUB2** (GRand "
"Unified Bootloader). GRUB2 replaces the old GRUB bootloader (also called "
"GRUB legacy)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:45
msgid ""
"The GRUB 2 configuration file is located under `/boot/grub2/grub.cfg` but "
"this file should not be edited directly."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:47
msgid ""
"The GRUB2 menu configuration settings are located under `/etc/default/grub` "
"and are used to generate the `grub.cfg` file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:57
msgid ""
"``` # cat /etc/default/grub GRUB_TIMEOUT=5 GRUB_DEFAULT=saved "
"GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true GRUB_TERMINAL_OUTPUT=\"console\" "
"GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"rd.lvm.lv=rhel/swap crashkernel=auto rd.lvm.lv=rhel/"
"root rhgb quiet net.ifnames=0\" GRUB_DISABLE_RECOVERY=\"true\" ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:59
msgid ""
"If changes are made to one or more of these parameters, the `grub2-mkconfig` "
"command must be run to regenerate the `/boot/grub2/grub.cfg` file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:63
msgid "``` [root] # grub2-mkconfig âo /boot/grub2/grub.cfg ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:66
msgid ""
"GRUB2 looks for the compressed kernel image (the `vmlinuz` file) in the `/"
"boot` directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:66
msgid ""
"GRUB2 loads the kernel image into memory and extracts the contents of the "
"`initramfs` image file into a temporary folder in memory using the `tmpfs` "
"file system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:68
msgid "### The kernel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The kernel starts the `systemd` process with PID 1.\n"
"```\n"
"root          1      0  0 02:10 ?        00:00:02 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd --switched-root --system --deserialize 23\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:75
msgid "### `systemd`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:77
msgid ""
"Systemd is the parent of all system processes. It reads the target of the `/"
"etc/systemd/system/default.target` link (e.g. `/usr/lib/systemd/system/multi-"
"user.target`) to determine the default target of the system. The file "
"defines the services to be started."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:79
msgid ""
"Systemd then places the system in the target-defined state by performing the "
"following initialization tasks:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Set the machine name"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Initialize the network"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Initialize SELinux"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Display the welcome banner"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid ""
"Initialize the hardware based on the arguments given to the kernel at boot "
"time"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Mount the file systems, including virtual file systems like /proc"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '7. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Clean up directories in /var"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '8. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:88
msgid "Start the virtual memory (swap)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:90
msgid "## Protecting the GRUB2 bootloader"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:92
msgid "Why protect the bootloader with a password?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:96
msgid ""
"Prevent *Single* user mode access - If an attacker can boot into single user "
"mode, he becomes the root user."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:96
msgid ""
"Prevent access to GRUB console - If an attacker manages to use GRUB console, "
"he can change its configuration or collect information about the system by "
"using the `cat` command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:96
msgid ""
"Prevent access to insecure operating systems. If there is a dual boot on the "
"system, an attacker can select an operating system like DOS at boot time "
"that ignores access controls and file permissions."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:98
msgid "To password protect the GRUB2 bootloader:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:100
msgid ""
"Remove `-unrestricted` from the main `CLASS=` statement in the `/etc/grub."
"d/10_linux` file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:102
msgid ""
"If a user has not yet been configured, use the `grub2-setpassword` command "
"to provide a password for the root user:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:106
msgid "``` # grub2-setpassword ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:108
msgid ""
"A `/boot/grub2/user.cfg` file will be created if it was not already present. "
"It contains the hashed password of the GRUB2."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    This command only supports configurations with a single root user.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:116
msgid ""
"``` [root]# cat /boot/grub2/user.cfg GRUB2_PASSWORD=grub.pbkdf2.sha512.10000."
"CC6F56....A21 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:118
msgid "Recreate the configuration file with the `grub2-mkconfig` command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:128
msgid ""
"``` [root]# grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg Generating grub "
"configuration file ...  Found linux image: /boot/vmlinuz-3.10.0-327.el7."
"x86_64 Found initrd image: /boot/initramfs-3.10.0-327.el7.x86_64.img Found "
"linux image: /boot/vmlinuz-0-rescue-f9725b0c842348ce9e0bc81968cf7181 Found "
"initrd image: /boot/initramfs-0-rescue-f9725b0c842348ce9e0bc81968cf7181.img "
"done ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:130
msgid "Restart the server and check."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:132
msgid ""
"All entries defined in the GRUB menu will now require a user and password to "
"be entered at each boot. The system will not boot a kernel without direct "
"user intervention from the console."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:135
msgid "When the user is requested, enter `root`;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:135
msgid ""
"When a password is requested, enter the password provided at the `grub2-"
"setpassword` command."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:137
msgid ""
"To protect only the editing of GRUB menu entries and access to the console, "
"the execution of the `grub2-setpassword` command is sufficient. There may be "
"cases where you have good reasons for doing only that. This might be "
"particularly true in a remote data center where entering a password each "
"time a server is rebooted is either difficult or impossible to do."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:139
msgid "## Systemd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:141
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Systemd* is a service manager for the Linux operating systems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:143
msgid "It is developed to:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:146
msgid "remain compatible with older SysV initialization scripts,"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:146
msgid ""
"provide many features, such as parallel start of system services at system "
"startup, on-demand activation of daemons, support for snapshots, or "
"management of dependencies between services."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:149
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    Systemd is the default initialization system since RedHat/CentOS 7.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:151
msgid "Systemd introduces the concept of systemd units."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:157
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Type         | File extension | Observation                              |\n"
"|--------------|----------------|------------------------------------------|\n"
"| Service unit | `.service`       | System service                           |\n"
"| Target unit  | `.target`        | A group of systemd units                 |\n"
"| Mount unit   | `.automount`     | An automatic mount point for file system |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:160
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"!!! Note\n"
"    There are many types of units: Device unit, Mount unit, Path unit, Scope unit, Slice unit, Snapshot unit, Socket unit, Swap unit, Timer unit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:162
msgid "Systemd supports system state snapshots and restore."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:164
msgid "Mount points can be configured as systemd targets."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:166
msgid ""
"At startup, systemd creates listening sockets for all system services that "
"support this type of activation and passes these sockets to these services "
"as soon as they are started. This makes it possible to restart a service "
"without losing a single message sent to it by the network during its "
"unavailability. The corresponding socket remains accessible and all messages "
"are queued."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:168
msgid ""
"System services that use D-BUS for their inter-process communications can be "
"started on demand the first time they are used by a client."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:170
msgid ""
"Systemd stops or restarts only running services. Previous versions (before "
"RHEL7) attempted to stop services directly without checking their current "
"status."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:172
msgid ""
"System services do not inherit any context (like HOME and PATH environment "
"variables). Each service operates in its own execution context."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:174
msgid ""
"All service unit operations are subject to a default timeout of 5 minutes to "
"prevent a malfunctioning service from freezing the system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:176
msgid "### Managing system services"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:178
msgid ""
"Service units end with the `.service` file extension and have a similar "
"purpose to init scripts. The `systemctl` command is used to `display`, "
"`start`, `stop`, `restart` a system service:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:188
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| systemctl                                 | Description                             |\n"
"|-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|\n"
"| systemctl start _name_.service            | Start a service                         |\n"
"| systemctl stop _name_.service             | Stops a service                         |\n"
"| systemctl restart _name_.service          | Restart a service                       |\n"
"| systemctl reload _name_.service           | Reload a configuration                  |\n"
"| systemctl status _name_.service           | Checks if a service is running          |\n"
"| systemctl try-restart _name_.service      | Restart a service only if it is running |\n"
"| systemctl list-units --type service --all | Display the status of all services      |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:190
msgid ""
"The `systemctl` command is also used for the `enable` or `disable` of system "
"a service and displaying associated services:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| systemctl                                | Description                                             |\n"
"|------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|\n"
"| systemctl enable _name_.service            | Activate a service                                      |\n"
"| systemctl disable _name_.service           | Disable a service                                       |\n"
"| systemctl list-unit-files --type service | Lists all services and checks if they are running       |\n"
"| systemctl list-dependencies --after      | Lists the services that start before the specified unit |\n"
"| systemctl list-dependencies --before     | Lists the services that start after the specified unit  |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:206
msgid ""
"``` systemctl stop nfs-server.service # or systemctl stop nfs-server ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:208
msgid "To list all units currently loaded:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:212
msgid "``` systemctl list-units --type service ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:214
msgid "To list all units to check if they are activated:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:218
msgid "``` systemctl list-unit-files --type service ```"
