"units into a chain of dependencies."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:256
msgid ""
"For example, the `graphical.target` unit, which is used to start a graphical "
"session, starts system services such as the **GNOME display manager** (`gdm."
"service`) or the **accounts service** (`accounts-daemon.service`) and also "
"activates the `multi-user.target` unit."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:258
msgid ""
"Similarly, the `multi-user.target` unit starts other essential system "
"services, such as **NetworkManager** (`NetworkManager.service`) or **D-Bus** "
"(`dbus.service`) and activates another target unit named `basic.target`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:266
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Target Units      | Description                                               |\n"
"|-------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------|\n"
"| poweroff.target   | Shuts down the system and turns it off                    |\n"
"| rescue.target     | Activates a rescue shell                                  |\n"
"| multi-user.target | Activates a multi-user system without graphical interface |\n"
"| graphical.target  | Activates a multi-user system with graphical interface    |\n"
"| reboot.target     | Shuts down and restarts the system                        |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:268
msgid "#### The default target"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:270
msgid "To determine which target is used by default:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:274
msgid "``` systemctl get-default ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:276
msgid ""
"This command searches for the target of the symbolic link located at `/etc/"
"systemd/system/default.target` and displays the result."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:281
msgid "``` $ systemctl get-default graphical.target ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:283
msgid "The `systemctl` command can also provide a list of available targets:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:307
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```\n"
"systemctl list-units --type target\n"
"UNIT                   LOAD   ACTIVE SUB    DESCRIPTION\n"
"basic.target           loaded active active Basic System\n"
"bluetooth.target       loaded active active Bluetooth\n"
"cryptsetup.target      loaded active active Encrypted Volumes\n"
"getty.target           loaded active active Login Prompts\n"
"graphical.target       loaded active active Graphical Interface\n"
"local-fs-pre.target    loaded active active Local File Systems (Pre)\n"
"local-fs.target        loaded active active Local File Systems\n"
"multi-user.target      loaded active active Multi-User System\n"
"network-online.target  loaded active active Network is Online\n"
"network.target         loaded active active Network\n"
"nss-user-lookup.target loaded active active User and Group Name Lookups\n"
"paths.target           loaded active active Paths\n"
"remote-fs.target       loaded active active Remote File Systems\n"
"slices.target          loaded active active Slices\n"
"sockets.target         loaded active active Sockets\n"
"sound.target           loaded active active Sound Card\n"
"swap.target            loaded active active Swap\n"
"sysinit.target         loaded active active System Initialization\n"
"timers.target          loaded active active Timers\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:309
msgid "To configure the system to use a different default target:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:313
msgid "``` systemctl set-default name.target ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:321
msgid ""
"``` # systemctl set-default multi-user.target rm '/etc/systemd/system/"
"default.target' ln -s '/usr/lib/systemd/system/multi-user.target' '/etc/"
"systemd/system/default.target' ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:323
msgid "To switch to a different target unit in the current session:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:327
msgid "``` systemctl isolate name.target ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:329
msgid ""
"The **Rescue mode** provides a simple environment to repair your system in "
"cases where it is impossible to perform a normal boot process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:331
msgid ""
"In `rescue mode`, the system attempts to mount all local file systems and "
"start several important system services, but does not enable a network "
"interface or allow other users to connect to the system at the same time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:333
msgid ""
"On Rocky 8, the `rescue mode` is equivalent to the old `single user mode` "
"and requires the root password."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:335
msgid ""
"To change the current target and enter `rescue mode` in the current session:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:339
msgid "``` systemctl rescue ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:341
#, no-wrap
msgid "**Emergency mode** provides the most minimalist environment possible and allows the system to be repaired even in situations where the system is unable to enter rescue mode. In the emergency mode, the system mounts the root file system only for reading. It will not attempt to mount any other local file system, will not activate any network interface, and will start some essential services.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:343
msgid ""
"To change the current target and enter emergency mode in the current session:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:347
msgid "``` systemctl emergency ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:349
msgid "#### Shutdown, suspension and hibernation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:351
msgid ""
"The `systemctl` command replaces a number of power management commands used "
"in previous versions:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:360
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"|Old command          | New command              | Description            |\n"
"|---------------------|--------------------------|------------------------|\n"
"| `halt`              | `systemctl halt`         |Shuts down the system.  |\n"
"| `poweroff`          | `systemctl poweroff`     |Turns off the system.   |\n"
"| `reboot`            | `systemctl reboot`       |Restarts the system.    |\n"
"| `pm-suspend`        | `systemctl suspend`      |Suspends the system.    |\n"
"| `pm-hibernate`      | `systemctl hibernate`    |Hibernates the system.  |\n"
"| `pm-suspend-hybrid` | `systemctl hybrid-sleep` |Hibernates and suspends the system.|\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:362
msgid "### The `journald` process"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:364
msgid ""
"Log files can, in addition to `rsyslogd`, also be managed by the `journald` "
"daemon which is a component of `systemd`."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:366
msgid ""
"The `journald` daemon captures Syslog messages, kernel log messages, "
"messages from the initial RAM disk and from the start of boot, as well as "
"messages written to the standard output and the standard error output of all "
"services, then indexes them and makes them available to the user."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:368
msgid ""
"The format of the native log file, which is a structured and indexed binary "
"file, improves searches and allows for faster operation, it also stores "
"metadata information, such as timestamps or user IDs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:370
msgid "### `journalctl` command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:372
msgid "The `journalctl` command displays the log files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:376
msgid "``` journalctl ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:378
msgid ""
"The command lists all log files generated on the system. The structure of "
"this output is similar to that used in `/var/log/messages/` but it offers "
"some improvements:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:383
msgid "the priority of entries is marked visually;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:383
msgid "timestamps are converted to the local time zone of your system;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:383
msgid "all logged data is displayed, including rotating logs;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:383
msgid "the beginning of a start is marked with a special line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:385
msgid "#### Using continuous display"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:387
msgid "With continuous display, log messages are displayed in real time."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:391
msgid "``` journalctl -f ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:393
msgid ""
"This command returns a list of the ten most recent log lines. The journalctl "
"utility then continues to run and waits for new changes to occur before "
"displaying them immediately."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:395
msgid "#### Filtering messages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:397
msgid ""
"It is possible to use different filtering methods to extract information "
"that fits different needs. Log messages are often used to track erroneous "
"behavior on the system. To view entries with a selected or higher priority:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:401
msgid "``` journalctl -p priority ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:403
msgid ""
"You must replace priority with one of the following keywords (or a number):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "debug (7),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "info (6),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "notice (5),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "warning (4),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "err (3),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "crit (2),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "alert (1),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:411
msgid "and emerg (0)."
msgstr ""
